{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/exploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-6242e5100a74", "time": 1683008663.937069, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/exploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-6242e5100a74/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Exploring the Trump Twitter Archive with NLTK | by Ednalyn C. De Dios | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Exploring the Trump Twitter Archive with NLTK", "description": "In this post, we\u2019ll explore the dataset provided by the Trump Twitter Archive. It\u2019s part one of the Exploring Trump series. For this project, we\u2019ll be using pandas and numpy for data manipulation\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://www.trumptwitterarchive.com/archive", "anchor_text": "Trump Twitter Archive", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/tagged/exploring-trump", "anchor_text": "Exploring Trump", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://github.com/ecdedios/into-heart-of-darkness", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "http://www.trumptwitterarchive.com/archive", "anchor_text": "Trump Twitter Archive", "paragraph_index": 36}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/exploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-with-spacy-fe557810717c", "anchor_text": "next post", "paragraph_index": 38}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/exploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-with-spacy-fe557810717c", "anchor_text": "use spaCy to extract named-entities", "paragraph_index": 38}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/ecdedios", "anchor_text": "Twitter", "paragraph_index": 40}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/ednalyn-de-dios/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 40}, {"url": "https://medium.com/@ednalyn.dedios/membership", "anchor_text": "https://medium.com/@ednalyn.dedios/membership", "paragraph_index": 42}], "all_paragraphs": ["In this post, we\u2019ll explore the dataset provided by the Trump Twitter Archive. It\u2019s part one of the Exploring Trump series.", "For this project, we\u2019ll be using pandas and numpy for data manipulation, matplotlib for visualizations, datetime for working with timestamps, unicodedata and regex for processing strings, and finally, nltk for natural language processing.", "Let\u2019s get started by firing up a Jupyter notebook!", "We\u2019re going to import pandas and matplotlib, and also set the display options for Jupyter so that the rows and columns are not truncated.", "Let\u2019s read the data into a dataframe. If you want to follow along, you can download the dataset here. This dataset contains President Trump\u2019s tweets from the moment he took office on January 20, 2017 to May 30, 2020.", "Let\u2019s look at the first five rows and see the number of records (rows) and fields (columns).", "Let\u2019s do a quick renaming of the columns to make it easier for us later.", "Let\u2019s drop the id column since it\u2019s not really relevant right now.", "Let\u2019s do a quick sanity check, this time let\u2019s also check the dtypes of the columns.", "We can see from the previous screenshot that the \u2018date_time\u2019 column is a string. Let\u2019s parse it to a timestamp.", "Let\u2019s add a column with \u2018datetime\u2019 that contains the timestamp information.", "Let\u2019s double-check the data range of our dataset.", "Let\u2019s see how many sources there are for the tweets.", "Let\u2019s only keep the ones that were made using the \u2018Twitter for iPhone\u2019 app.", "We should drop the old \u2018date_time\u2019 column and the \u2018source\u2019 column as well.", "Let\u2019s see how many are retweets.", "Let\u2019s make another dataframe that contains only retweets and drop the \u2018is_retweet\u2019 column.", "Back on the original dataframe, let\u2019s remove the retweets from the dataset and drop the \u2018is_retweet\u2019 column altogether.", "Let\u2019s explore both of the dataframes and answer a few questions.", "The graph below shows that the President most frequently tweets around 12pm. He also tweets the least around 8am.", "The graph below shows that the President most frequently tweets on Wednesday. He also tweets the least on Thursday.", "Let\u2019s import regex so we can use it to parse the text and isolate the Twitter handles of the original tweets. In the code below, we add another column that contains the Twitter handle.", "Let\u2019s create another dataframe that will contain only the original Twitter handles and their associated number of retweets.", "Let\u2019s check the data real quick:", "Let\u2019s visualize the results real quick so we can get an idea if the data is disproportionate or not.", "The graph below shows that the President likes to retweet the tweets from \u2018@realDonaldTrump\u2019.", "Let\u2019s look at the top 5 tweets that were retweeted the most by others based on the original Twitter handle.", "Let\u2019s start with the ones with \u2018@realDonaldTrump\u2019.", "Let\u2019s find out how many of the retweets are favorited by others.", "Surprisingly, none of the retweets seemed to have been favorited by anybody. Weird.", "To do some n-gram ranking, we need to import unicodedata and nltk. We also need to specify additional stopwords that we may need to exclude from our analysis.", "Here are a few of my favorite functions for natural language processing:", "Let\u2019s look at the top 10 bigrams in the df dataframe using the \u2018tweet\u2019 column.", "And now, for the top 10 trigrams:", "Let\u2019s use the viz_bigrams() function and visualize the bigrams.", "Similarly, let\u2019s use the viz_trigrams() function and visualize the trigrams.", "Using basic Python and the nltk library, we\u2019ve explored the dataset from the Trump Twitter Archive and did some n-gram ranking out of it.", "Thank you for reading! Exploratory data analysis uses a lot of techniques and we\u2019ve only explored a few on this post. I encourage you to keep practicing and employ other techniques to derive insights from data.", "In the next post, we shall continue our journey into Trump Twitter Archive and use spaCy to extract named-entities from the same dataset.", "If you want to learn more about my journey from slacker to data scientist, check out the article below:", "You can reach me on Twitter or LinkedIn.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Machine Learning Engineer / Data Scientist / Python Developer / Food Lover https://medium.com/@ednalyn.dedios/membership"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F6242e5100a74&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fexploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-6242e5100a74&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fexploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-6242e5100a74&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fexploring-the-trump-twitter-archive-6242e5100a74&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.c